(664, 10, '2015-03-31 03:36:18', '2015-03-31 03:36:18', 'Last week, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) announced a major update to the rules and regulations that currently apply to equity crowdfunding. The announced updates constitute a major step forward for this new crowdfunding method, being considerably less restrictive than existing guidelines as listed in <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/01/61469-the-funding-cap-on-title-iii-retail-crowdfunding-is-pointless/">Title III Equity Crowdfunding</a> of the Jumpstart Our Business Startups Act (<a href="https://www.sec.gov/spotlight/jobs-act.shtml">JOBS Act</a>). The move comes at a great surprise for industry watchers in light of their radical departure from Title III''s <a href="https://www.sec.gov/comments/s7-09-13/s70913-533.pdf">onerous, restrictive, and expensive</a> listing requirements.\r\n\r\nUnder current and expiring regulations, issuers are required to list their Crowdfunding equity offerings in <a href="http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-113hhrg80819/pdf/CHRG-113hhrg80819.pdf">each and every State nation-wide</a> where they solicited investors, with the expensive <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">compliance and filing expenses to boot</a>. No more, starting June 2015, equity crowdfunders will be able to overall raise more, advertise to a wider audience, with better streamlined filing requirements as they become able to pre-empt <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">individual State approval</a>.\r\n\r\nThe announced changes also allow issuers to take advantage of more freedom in determining the pace at which they seek financing from public offerings. A startup is now <a href="http://www.dentons.com/~/media/PDFs/Insights/2014/January/SEC_JOBS_Act.pdf">allowed to ease its way from</a> minor Tier I ($20 Millions) public offerings for every 12 months period, to subsequent rounds of heftier Tier II (up to $50 Millions), in a way that in no way precludes them from the more standard initial public offering (IPO). Given the <a href="http://qz.com/205374/tech-ipos-went-from-frenzy-to-fizzle-in-about-a-month/">tepid environment</a> in capital markets as of early 2015 for tech-start-up IPOs, with many cancelled or <a href="http://qz.com/204779/boxs-highly-anticipated-ipo-should-hit-in-late-may/">flopped</a>, it is now easier for issuers to test market appetite <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnusFzqY20">prior to major listing</a> announcements and legal, regulatory, expenses.\r\n\r\nHere are six key take-always you should be aware of as <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">Regulation A+</a> comes into effect in June 2015:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong> Startup companies can now equity crowdfund up to $20 or $50 millions per year.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2013/12/28633-sec-approves-new-rules-regulation/">Under the new incoming regulation</a>, startup companies will be able to raise up to either $20 millions under Tier I of Regulation A+ or $50 millions under Tier II upon submitting two years of audited, or simply reviewed, financial statements. They will additionally be able to host subsequent rounds of crowdfunding every 12 months, without meeting a particular notional cumulative cap, provided that they continue to meet <a href="http://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2015/33-9741.pdf">NASAA Coordinated Review</a> standards.\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li><strong> Investment companies are not allowed to equity crowdfund under the new rules. </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnusFzqY20">changes</a> coming to applicable equity crowdfunding rounds exclude private equity funds, hedge funds, and venture capital funds, investment companies in short, from taking advantage of this new way to raise startup capital from the public. This is a welcome development, as it prevents deep-pocketed funds from crowding out smaller seekers of the general public’s demand for crowdfunded startup <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">shares</a>.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li><strong> No restrictions on the advertisement of offerings.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nOne of the most significant aspects of the crowdfunding rules to come makes it <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">legal for a startup company to advertise</a> its share offerings to the general public, without restrictions, in mainstream media. This rule means that for many companies, you can expect Twitter, Facebook, television, and other major social media platforms to feature advertisements for equity crowdfunding shares as new products get announced.\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n	<li><strong> No restrictions on who can invest, no proof of income required from investors.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe large majority of public equity offerings, offerings of shares for free public distribution and exchange, <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2013/12/28633-sec-approves-new-rules-regulation/">were under strict limit</a> as to who could invest. Households with a combined income of $200,000 or a net worth of $1 million and accredited investors were the only ones allowed to participate. Under the <a href="http://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2015/33-9741.pdf">Regulation A+</a>, investments as small as $100 are possible, provided that interested investors can show that the funds are less or equal to the higher of either 10% of their net income or 10% of their declared net-worth. No additional paperwork are required to prove specific investors’ incomes.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n	<li><strong> No disclosure requirements for Tier I &amp; annual disclosure filings for Tier II rounds.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nTier I offerings, those raising up to $20 Millions will only have to show reviewed financial statements. Meanwhile, Tier II offerings, up to $50 Million dollars, will be required to file annual disclosures, semi-annual reports, and current reports. These are respectively simply mini-equivalents of the better-known 10-K, 10-Q, and Form 8-K filings for mainstream listed companies.\r\n<ol start="6">\r\n	<li><strong> Free transfer, fungibility of all securities issued during equity crowdfunding rounds.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nInvestors in equity crowdfunded rounds will be able to freely buy and re-sell shares acquired during crowdfunding rounds under <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">Regulation A+</a>. This change in regulation means that observers can expect a vibrant secondary market for equity crowdfunding’s shares, adding an element of liquidity to the new instrument.\r\n\r\nThe new set of crowdfunding rules announced by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) on March 25th is proving to be a bombshell. It paves the way for the creation of new venture exchanges for shares resulting from this new way to raise capital to a much larger set of investors. It should altogether make it easier for emerging startups to circumvent venture capital’s storied gatekeepers, and take their business cases directly to an eager mass public.', 'What Will Crowdfunding in 2015 Look Like?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'what-will-crowdfunding-in-2015-look-like', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=664', 0, 'post', '', 0),
