(695, 10, '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We have already examined equity crowdfunding in the context of Latin America before: specifically, we featured Chile in one of our prior “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” pieces. Now, let’s take a look at Brazil: another Latin American nation that seems to have experienced a crowdfunding boom.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_730" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Brazil.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-730" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Brazil-300x250.png" alt="Brazil Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Brazil Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nAccording to most sources, Brazil’s crowdfunding ecosystem is already “healthy and growing”. Specifically, the World Bank has noted that Brazil has over seventeen large crowdfunding sites, including Catarse – a site that calls itself “the biggest crowdfunding community in Brazil”, and that has helped over one thousand projects raise over $4.1 million in total. The practice first arrived in Brazil in 2009 through a site called Vakinha, which helped people fund businesses, projects, and personal matters (<em>e.g.</em>, plastic surgeries, new cars).\r\n\r\nThe legal status of crowdfunding in Brazil, presumably, remained unclear until about 2012, but in that year, Brazilian governing bodies still said that <a href="https://www.virtualwallstreet.com/crowdfund-brazil.shtml">no restrictions</a> existed on what could be done within the nation. Even in 2012, Brazil had about twenty to thirty crowdfunding sites: a good start, and one comparable to that of other countries! However, since, Brazil’s crowdfunding system has faced some obstacles: namely, the fact that doing business in Brazil often comes with the custo Brasil (the Brazil Cost): in other words, with countless bureaucratic and legal complications. Entrepreneurs unfamiliar with Brazilian restrictions may have a hard time making crowdfunding ends meet in the region, and Brazil won’t be of much help, given that it lacks the legal framework and proper e-commerce environment to successfully implement crowdfunding on a nation scale.\r\n\r\nMany Brazilians also feel that Brazil has <a href="http://www.crowdvalley.com/news/brazilian-crowdfunding-post-world-cup">not as yet</a> exploited the whole of its equity crowdfunding potential – a potential that exists at both the domestic and the international levels. While, as described, there is a great domestic interest in crowdfunding, Brazilian culture, arts, and projects are also valued internationally. Assuming that Brazil plays its cards right, crowdfunding could be utilized to attract international investors to Brazilian projects, thus further bolstering the economy. Brazil could also work with the remainder of South America, integrating in a Latin American platform that would bring in yet more investors, and service yet more entrepreneurs.\r\n\r\nConversely, many European and American platforms have recognized that Latin America – and Brazil in particular – is a compelling region to do crowdfunding with. These platforms have begun translating their websites in order to attract Brazilian investors; crowdfunding journalist Janet Gunter believes this is the result of companies’ recognition of the interest shown in crowdfunding by the Brazilian government.\r\n\r\nBrazilian platforms, conversely, have not dominantly been translated into English, or into any other language. This, actually, appears to be true for the entirety of Latin America: platforms and crowdfunding information sources are dominantly in Spanish or Portuguese, but do not appear in English translations. This is problematic, because it prevents Brazil and other Latin American countries from communicating with such crowdfunding hubs as Canada, the USA, and the UK. These Brazilian platforms also often lack international payment methods; this is non-ideal because many international investors are, as mentioned, interested in what Brazil has to offer; if they cannot contribute to Brazilian campaigns, Brazilian entrepreneurs have less potential capital at their disposal.\r\n\r\nNevertheless, <a href="http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/brazilian-crowdfunding">many platforms</a> are up and about within Brazil itself, which creates ample opportunity for the Brazilian community. Demohour (which we have already examined in other Latin American countries) and Catarse are relatively successful, which means that Brazil is a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/hsbc/2014/07/09/will-the-world-cup-spark-or-stifle-brazils-growth/">promising</a> emerging market for crowdfunding! Movere is another main crowdfunding website in Brazil! Some other platforms include Benfeitoria (a site focused on projects in accessibility, culture, education, music, and fashion) and Queremos (a platform that deals with financing foreign events (<em>e.g.</em>, concerts)).', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Brazil in Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-brazil-in-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=695', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(696, 10, '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Thus far, in our “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series, we’ve examined North America, Latin America, parts of Asia, and parts of Europe in trying to gauge the scope of equity crowdfunding on a global level. Now, let’s take a look at another country in Europe, and see how equity crowdfunding is performing within it. The focus of this article is Italy, a region in which equity crowdfunding, it would seem, is again experiencing a considerable boom!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_733" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Italian.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-733" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Italian-300x250.png" alt="Italian Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Italian Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs early as <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">2012</a>, the Italian parliament issued a law on startups that made equity crowdfunding possible. Within one year of publication of these regulations, nine portals had been authorized in Italy; by 2014, each of the first three had raised capital of over one million Euros.\r\n\r\nWhile things look like they’re off to a relatively good start for Italy, then, it should be noted that problems still exist for Italy where crowdfunding is concerned. The <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">first challenge</a> is, as always, regulation – there are relatively strong limitations introduced by legislation and the CONSOB regulation. Specifically, only some companies were, until recently, allowed to raise risk capital online – namely, “innovative start-ups” – which limits crowdfunding to high-risk enterprises; while this has now been changed, the equity crowdfunding space is still restricted. The <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">second challenge</a> is that the Italian market has a propensity for risk, and it may therefore be difficult to reach the size necessary to sustain a few equity crowdfunding platforms concurrently.\r\n\r\nInnovation is nevertheless continually being had in Italy: 2015 will see the Global Entrepreneurship Congress and EXPO in Milan, making this an important year for Italian crowdfunding history. Italy was also the <a href="http://www.telecomitalia.com/tit/en/ambiente-sociale/cos-e-il-crowdfunding.html">first</a> country in Europe to have a law that regulates equity crowdfunding, predominantly because of the economic crisis that struck Italy in 2008, and resulted in a decree created to stimulate economic growth in the country. Equity crowdfunding is seen by this bill as a tool that can greatly ameliorate Italy’s concentration of innovative start-ups through exploiting the Web.\r\n\r\nAs of 2015, Italy also expanded equity crowdfunding to include “<a href="http://www.growvc.com/blog/2015/01/italy-expands-equity-crowdfunding-to-innovative-smes/">innovative SMEs</a>” – firms with a more than €50 million annual turnover, and that meet at least one of the following three requirements: 3% of either sales or costs are attributable to R&amp;D activities, one third of employees have a degree or one fifth of employees are doing or have done a doctorate program, and the company owns a patent. This means that equity crowdfunding now has a bigger user base in the country, which, in turn, translates to more opportunities for investors to pitch in to!\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, it’s clear that equity crowdfunding is up and running in Italy: while its regulations were a tad restrictive from the get-go, Italy was the first country to adapt to equity crowdfunding, and to consider it meaningful enough to craft a related regulatory regime. Now, several equity crowdfunding portals exist in Italy, so opportunities for the investor working with either innovative start-ups or innovate SMEs have dramatically increased. While we are certain that many other portals exist, here are some that have previously been featured on <a href="http://www.crowdclan.com/equity-crowdfunding-portals-in-italy/">Crowdclan.com</a>:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Derev: first created in 2012, and now an international network for universities, corporations, and other institutions with an interest in arts, culture, technology, politics, and activism</li>\r\n	<li>SiamoSoci: its primary objective is to accelerate the process of growing startups; it occupies about 3.7% of the national seed and venture capital market – a large portal, in other words</li>\r\n	<li>StarsUp: the first CONSOB-authorized portal, this one seeks to pair good ideas with valuable consultants</li>\r\n	<li>Unicaseed: a brokerage company offering trading and investment counselling in conjunction with crowdfunding</li>\r\n	<li>WeAreStarting: a 2013 portal geared at increasing early entrepreneurs’ visibility</li>\r\n	<li>Two other portals include Assiteca Crowd and CrowdfundMe, respectively one of the first equity crowdfunding portals in Italy, and one of the newest portals around</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Italian Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-italian-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=696', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(697, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX really believe that equity crowdfunding is the way to go. Investors! You are living in an exciting era, one that promises you an abundance of opportunities and also the chance to get to know about those opportunities in a very agile and efficient manner. What makes the process of investing even more exciting now is the presence of an entirely new ecosystem that is characterized by several hundreds of equity portals that facilitate all stakeholders who are part of an investment. At KoreConX, we have also launched an equity portal system which not only supports crowdfunding platforms, but also looks after capital markets for you. We believe that with the help of our equity portal, called the eco-system infrastructure platform (ESIP), you will be facilitated throughout your investment during different its phases, such as pre-during-post crowdfunding transactions. Our equity portal will help you by maintaining due diligence of issuers, data repository, or deal room, and will also help in shareholder management and communications, something that is quite revolutionary in today’s modern world of transparency. Finally, for every type of investor, whether you are a CEO, a lawyer, auditor, or even a third-party provider, we have provided a safe and secure platform with a single point of entry to prevent leakage and mishandling of corporate or personal information.\r\n\r\nToday, due to cloud computing, elegant software solutions, efficient distribution channels, learning about validation and testing techniques, globalized sharing of information, social media, and online marketing, the world of business and commerce holds more potential than ever. You have been given the opportunity to not only know about businesses in a more transparent manner, but also to invest in them via modern investment opportunities like equity crowdfunding. Equity crowdfunding, as opposed to crowdfunding alone, is a more recent global phenomenon which has opened an entirely new world for investors of any kind. While crowdfunding alone only lead to recognition for financial support in the success of the company, equity crowdfunding now allows investors to have a stake in a company which is still in its infancy stages. Due to the nature of this investment opportunity, the business landscape has been reformed, and continues to be so in significant ways. While the traditional business landscape favored large investments typically facilitated by venture capital firms to companies which were far advanced in terms of their development, the new business landscape is being quickly filled up with small businesses early on in their development – start-ups, in other words – which have a tremendous advantage in terms of potential, but also come with a larger risk from an investor’s point of view. However, if treaded carefully, the investor can make shrewd decisions about equity crowdfunding, just like any other investment.\r\n\r\nIf you are an American investor today, enjoying the entrepreneurship boom and concurrent rise in hundreds of equity crowdfunding portals, you have, as discussed above, many, many opportunities. Not only is this phenomenon reaching epic proportions – it is also very recent: the US only legalized the equity crowdfunding landscape last year (March 2014); since legalization, the US equity crowdfunding landscape has seen the inception of over 1000 websites dedicated to this phenomenon. Equity crowdfunding is expected to grow even more this year, for up to $17 billion after having been forecasted for $10 billion in 2014. The sheer number of platforms dedicated to this phenomenon is very good news for any American investor. Anybody today can contribute to a concept that they feel related to or interested in, and can become part of the company’s journey. While the majority of these platforms require that you be an accredited investor, you still have options with other platforms which do not require that on an absolute basis.\r\n\r\nHere, then, is a short list of equity crowdfunding platforms in the US via which you can invest:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fangel.co%2F&amp;ei=XSE9VYi2E7DdsATbzoH4DA&amp;usg=AFQjCNG07Amw4_R3yedobbYoJNxKqpcaGw&amp;sig2=cC0NpjUFEnMwX0waGxmWYQ&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">AngelList</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fcircleup.com%2F&amp;ei=gyE9VZTyG4rmsATYmICwDQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNG0joLuK4FU07n2-SDf0ijhiWXLoQ&amp;sig2=5j8ImQ6x6ZLltmPGjeKzrw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">CircleUp</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCAQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.earlyshares.com%2F&amp;ei=kiE9VcifHuLLsAT034CYBw&amp;usg=AFQjCNG9lZBbjRxNnHF4TNrYWLZak-Tu8w&amp;sig2=xeSMCx3V1WSYf2pQri_r_Q&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Early Shares</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCkQFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.equitynet.com%2F&amp;ei=niE9VaWDPLHmsATT8oCQAg&amp;usg=AFQjCNEQwPyzqFmqiQjfUoI-Li8m2HE38w&amp;sig2=rq1OWfbucEduHKIsvS-Whg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">EquityNet</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fundable.com%2F&amp;ei=rCE9VY3MFfOIsQS4wYDwDA&amp;usg=AFQjCNH7YfJxcp-qeioDqEce0_15nTNh-Q&amp;sig2=X2bp_QRbVPK1lqTpqUD86g&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Fundable</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&am