(720, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a past series, we examined equity crowdfunding in several global locales – specifically, we looked into crowdfunding ecosystems across Canada, the USA, Mexico, China, Australia, Chile, Brazil, the UK, and Italy: across, in other words, North America, Latin America, Asia, Oceania, and Europe. As is evident, then, equity crowdfunding is a truly global phenomenon, and the truth is that you can crowdfund nearly anywhere!\r\n\r\nTo put things into perspective, let’s take a look at some <a href="https://fundwisdom.com/article/fengjiayi/global-equity-crowdfunding-uk-us">World Bank data</a> from 2012, when crowdfunding had really just begun rearing its head in many countries. In that year alone, the following countries all had between one and three hundred crowdfunding investing platforms (CFIs): the USA, France, Italy, the UK, Spain, Netherlands, Germany, Brazil, Canada, Australia, South Africa, India, the Russian Federation, Belgium, Hong Kong, China, the UAE, and Estonia. Since, New Zealand, Sweden, and the East African country of Kenya have <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/wilschroter/2014/07/09/crowdfunding-around-the-world/2/">all engaged</a> in crowdfunding initiatives.\r\n\r\nIn sum, then, crowdfunding is essentially everywhere. But where <em>precisely</em> is “everywhere”? To quantify this generalization, here’s a list of places in the world where you can <em>definitely </em>do equity crowdfunding:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Canada: Canada is rife with crowdfunding and crowdfunding education, with events like the <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/2015-canadian-crowdfunding-summit-early-bird-registration-now-open/">Canadian Crowdfunding Summit</a> occurring for the first time in 2015, and organizations like the National Crowdfunding Association of Canada (<a href="http://ncfacanada.org/2015-canadian-crowdfunding-summit-early-bird-registration-now-open/">NCFA</a>) spear-heading the equity crowdfunding movement; over <a href="https://fundwisdom.com/article/fengjiayi/global-equity-crowdfunding-uk-us">thirty-four</a> Canadian equity crowdfunding platforms exist, as of 2012!</li>\r\n	<li>The USA: The USA is perhaps the most active country in the world where equity crowdfunding is concerned – close to 1000 equity crowdfunding sites exist in the USA as of March 2014! Further, equity crowdfunding is expected to grow in the USA in 2015 – the market may well hit <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jorge-newbery/crowdfunding-is-growing-u_b_4980206.html">$17 billion</a> this year</li>\r\n	<li>France: France has many, many crowdfunding platforms on <em>The Soho Loft’s </em><a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">list</a> of global crowdfunding sites; they span personal, creative, entrepreneurial, and social projects, as well as sites that specifically support students, musicians, sports, journalism, books, fashion, film, and more</li>\r\n	<li>Italy: Italy embraced crowdfunding as early as 2012; as of 2015, Italy has expanded its equity crowdfunding regulations to <a href="http://www.growvc.com/blog/2015/01/italy-expands-equity-crowdfunding-to-innovative-smes/">include</a> innovative small and medium businesses in crowdfunding activities; many crowdfunding portals exist in the country, as listed on <a href="http://www.crowdclan.com/equity-crowdfunding-portals-in-italy/">com</a></li>\r\n	<li>The UK: The UK is another crowdfunding hub, like the USA and Canada; <em>The Telegraph</em>’s Kyle Caldwell has compiled a <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/investing/10435276/Which-are-the-best-crowdfunding-websites.html">list</a> of some of the best crowdfunding websites in the region</li>\r\n	<li>Spain: Spain has <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">several</a> crowdfunding platforms, including Verkami.com, Lanzanos.com, Injoinet.com, Goteo.org, and Fandyu.com</li>\r\n	<li>The Netherlands: Local crowdfunding platforms <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">include</a>nl, 4just1.com, Greenwish.nl, Sellaband.com, Africaunsigned.com, Talentboek.nl, and Nieuwspost.nl</li>\r\n	<li>Brazil: Even in 2012, Brazil had about twenty to thirty crowdfunding sites; while many Brazilians feel that equity crowdfunding is yet to hit its potential in the country, <a href="http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/brazilian-crowdfunding">many platforms</a> already exist within the country, creating ample opportunity for investors and entrepreneurs; these include Demohour and Catarse, both of which are considerably successful</li>\r\n	<li>Australia: Crowdfunding is most definitely not prohibited in Australia, though Australian crowdfunding regulation is a bit behind other places; several noteworthy platforms exist, including <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Chuffed</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">GiggedIn</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">OzCrowd</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Cleantechfundr</a>, and the Australian Small Scale Offerings Board (<a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">ASSOB</a>)</li>\r\n	<li>China: <em>Forbes</em>’s <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/">Conor Roche</a> believes China could “kick off a new wave in equity crowdfunding that might even leave the European and US-based philanthropic and rewards-based crowdfunding movements in the dust”! Specifically, on the basis of a look at China’s economic ecosystem, the World Bank has presumably suggested that Chinese crowdfunding could become a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">$50 billion</a> industry by just 2025</li>\r\n	<li>Mexico: Mexico is actually a relatively reasonable candidate for an equity crowdfunding boom, what with its “bustling engineering and innovation community”, as <em>Forbes’s</em> <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">Chance Barnett</a> describes it, and an ecosystem “ripe for entrepreneurial growth”; Crowdfunder has entered Mexico with <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">mx</a>, and several leading platforms are following suite</li>\r\n	<li>Chile: Crowdfunding is a large phenomenon in Latin America; the Chilean economy, what with its focus on innovation and <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">entrepreneurship</a>, ideally sets the stage for crowdfunding in the country; while <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">some entrepreneurs</a> point out that Chileans may not as yet be as Internet-savvy as they’d need to be in order to embrace crowdfunding, <a href="http://www.universocrowdfunding.com/plataformas-de-crowdfunding-en-latinoamerica/">several platforms</a> already exist within the country</li>\r\n	<li>Turkey: Several <a href="http://fonlabeni.com/">Turkish platforms</a> exist, including Fonlabeni, Fongogo, and Biayda</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">Other countries</a> with crowdfunding include Germany, Argentina, Norway, Austria, Finland, South Korea, Japan, the Philippines, Ireland, Israel, Portugal, the Czech Republic, the Ukraine, Kenya, Sweden, New Zealand, Estonia, the United Arab Emirates, India, Belgium, Hong Kong, the Russian Federation, and South Africa. (If you’re looking for specific sites, head <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">here</a> for a relatively comprehensive list of global crowdfunding platforms!)\r\n\r\nSo, now that we’ve established where in the world you <em>can </em>do equity crowdfunding, where is it impossible? Apparently, Singapore! Despite the fact that Singapore is a huge financial center, crowdfunding platforms still appear to be <a href="http://www.mas.gov.sg/regulations-and-financial-stability/regulations-guidance-and-licensing/securities-futures-and-funds-management/forms/collective-investment-schemes.aspx">illegal</a> in the country.', 'Where in the world can you equity crowdfund?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'world-can-equity-crowdfund', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=720', 0, 'post', '', 0);
