(741, 10, '2015-05-11 19:16:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX see crowdfunding, especially equity crowdfunding, as a game changer that will modify the way investments take place. While in the previous article we discussed the factors that come into play when entrepreneurs go through the pre-crowdfunding stage, in this article we will discuss more specifically the things entrepreneurs face during the actual process of crowdfunding. In order to better understand this, we need to first understand that equity crowdfunding is not the only form of crowdfunding. There are several other forms of crowdfunding out there that existed even before equity crowdfunding. There is donation-based crowdfunding, lending based crowdfunding, reward based crowdfunding, and, finally, equity based crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nIn <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">donation-based crowdfunding</a>, the crowd donates money for a charitable or a humanitarian cause. This kind of crowdfunding has been in place for a long time, and is usually prevalent in times of crisis or in front of a pressing need. People who donate money recognize a larger good for the society and do not seek any financial returns on their money. However, in <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">rewards based crowdfunding</a>, the funders receive rewards in return for their funds in the form of a product that is yet not in the market, or services that are not offered by the company to general public. In rewards based crowdfunding, the rewards are set before the funding takes place, so the funder expects the rewards in return for his investment at the time when he is funding the company. Finally, <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">equity based crowd funding</a>, which as we highlighted above is the most recent and impactful form of crowdfunding, involves real-time investment and financial returns. The people who support the business idea in the form of their capital receive a share or equity in the company. These investors then become shareholders who become part of that company’s success or failure. Compared to the three forms of crowdfunding discussed above, <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">lending based crowdfunding</a> involves people supporting a business idea with their capital, but these people do not contribute their capital on a permanent basis, instead they require that their capital be returned on top of pre-defined interest after a set period of time.\r\n\r\nNow that we have discussed different forms of crowdfunding, and we know the specific attributes of each kind of crowdfunding, we will focus on solely equity crowdfunding. During the process of equity crowdfunding, the parties involved – the entrepreneur, the investor and the equity crowdfunding portal – all converge to make an investment happen. This usually involves the entrepreneur applying to be listed on the equity crowdfunding portal for which he submits the necessary documentation to complete due diligence. Once this is completed, the entrepreneur then proceeds to submit more business related documents, such as financial statements and a business plan, to be displayed for interested investors on equity crowdfunding portal.  The equity crowdfunding portal is situated in the middle with the task of optimizing the entrepreneur’s listing to the interested investors, and at the same time carries out effective due diligence of interested investors by checking if they are eligible for an investment. If both the investor and entrepreneur satisfy the eligibility criteria, they are allowed to come up with a settlement involving the investor contributing a settled amount of capital in return for a settled amount of the company’s stake or share in return. Once this has happened, the money is deposited in an escrow account of the equity crowdfunding portal before being submitted to the entrepreneur. In return, the investor is provided with the necessary documents that confirm the investor’s share in the company and the entrepreneur is requested to sign final regulatory documents and bring all shareholders onto the sam epage with regards to future communication and the company’s quarterly updates.\r\n\r\nIn many cases, however, the entrepreneur is not able to collect enough as much capital as he or she initially decided to collect from one or more investors. In this case, <a href="https://texas.trucrowd.com/how-it-works">the deal does not happen</a>, and the money is returned from the escrow account back to the investor. In contrast, many outstanding business projects receive much more capital than the emerging business sought out to collect. In this case, the extra funds are managed to enhance the company’s global reach via marketing, or the money is channeled into long-term goals with the consent of all shareholders.', 'What happens in the “during” stage of crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 19:16:48', '2015-05-11 19:16:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=741', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(742, 10, '2015-05-11 19:17:16', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX support and endorse equity crowdfunding as a truly global and democratic phenomenon which although is in its <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">infancy stages</a>, holds the potential to completely revamp the way investments are conducted in our world. Because the concept of crowdfunding is very powerful and appealing to both investors and entrepreneurs, several people have come forward suggesting what they think are golden rules for crowdfunding. But before we suggest the golden rules for crowdfunding from our point of view, it is important that we look at all forms of crowdfunding so that the golden rules are applicable to all forms of crowdfunding and not just one.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are<a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/"> four types of crowdfunding</a>, each of which requires funds to be contributed from the crowd or the public towards a party, a business person or an organization. The nature of the funds provided however varies with the type of crowdfunding. In <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">rewards based crowdfunding</a>, the crowd contributes capital in return for predetermined awards such as products or services which are in huge demand but are not for sale yet. In <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">lending based crowdfunding</a>, the crowd who invests in a business concept lends money only to be returned at a later date with added interest charges. In <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">donation based crowdfunding</a>, the crowd donates money for a cause they seem worthy of supporting, and this usually happens in a state of crisis or for a charity. Finally in <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">equity crowdfunding</a>, the investor invests capital in return for stake or share in the company. This means that the investor becomes part of the company and has active interest in how the company does due to financial returns that the investor seeks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn all forms of crowdfunding, we believe that the number one golden rule that determines whether crowdfunding will realistically happen or not is the presence of market or niche. The entrepreneur before seeking any form of crowdfunding needs to see what he has to offer, and whether his offerings solve a problem, meet any market needs or whether his product or services create a market of its own. This can be found out by doing extensive research of the market, surveying for any potential competitors both globally and locally. Finally the best way to get a feel of whether there is a market, the entrepreneur needs to sell or put his idea in the market <a href="http://crowdfunding-guide.hwtrek.com/?chapter=chapter-5">through social media</a>. Several business ideas that go through successful pre launch or pre crowdfunding validate the process of testing the business concept even before it enters crowdfunding platform.\r\n\r\nThe second golden rule of crowdfunding after one has determined market demand is to carefully plan out the business plan, the <a href="http://crowdfunding-guide.hwtrek.com/?chapter=chapter-5">elevator pitch and design the crowdfunding campaign</a>. This needs to be done approximately six months in advance. The entrepreneur needs to know which kinds of crowd does he want to appeal to based on what his audience would be. He or she needs to carefully determine which kind of equity crowdfunding portal will be right fit for his business. He or she will also have to plan out whether the business needs a specific advisor and what kind of equity should be given to the advisor based on where the company stands and how much will it profit after the advisors’ contributions will come into effect.\r\n\r\nThe third and final golden rule we believe for crowdfunding is to always be cautious. Many of entrepreneurs launching a product feel very strongly about their product. It is quite possible that the entrepreneurs overestimate the demand and the market based on social media presence. It is also quite possible that the emerging business incurs loans or debts predicated upon potential rise of the business. However, it is never wise and sometimes, the plan does not come the way we intend it to proceed. Being cautious allows entrepreneurs to proceed with careful optimism, where the entrepreneurs scale everything appropriately by taking independent consultation advice from professionals and friends at each stage of business and therefore make informed decisions. This helps new entrepreneurs avoid some big mistakes and keeps them proceeding towards their vision.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile there are many golden rules, we feel the above three rules are quite important and therefore if followed properly, they can serve the entrepreneur and his emerging business well. Although not a golden rule, we also feel that entrepreneurs should work towards personal fulfillment of the investors. This can be achieved by supporting investors future projects and showing gratitude for their assistance towards the entrepreneur’s own business. This token of courtesy ensures that the investors always feel valuable to the company and maintain sincere concern for the wellbeing of the company just like the entrepreneur does. This also helps in building trust and transparency which goes far beyond the stage of crowdfunding, and therefore should be sought through the journey of the company.', 'What is the Golden Rule of crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 19:17:16', '2015-05-11 19:17:16', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=742', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(743, 10, '2015-05-11 19:17:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX feel that you are living in an exciting era. The world of democratic investments is on its way. While there are many <a href="http://www.bruegel.org/publications/publication-detail/publication/844-improving-the-role-of-equity-crowdfunding-in-europes-capital-markets/">frustrating legislative roadblocks</a> that we are facing at present time, there are still many opportunities that lay ahead of this tremendous truly global phenomenon. In order to capture the immensity of potential that lays ahead of us, we need to educate people globally about the process of crowdfunding and what are the stages before and it. In other articles, we have illuminated the process itself and other facets to it. In this article, we will shed some light on what goes around pre-crowdfunding. What should an entrepreneur be concerned about before he launches his product on the crowdfunding portal? What are the factors that distinguish one entrepreneur’s result in the crowdfunding stage versus the other? In essence then, we will look at what prepares entrepreneurs better. The more they are prepared, the more efficient they are at recouping benefits from the word go.\r\n\r\nPre-crowdfunding marks the time when the product is not yet launched, but the entrepreneur prepares himself to have a successful launch. It is the time during which the entrepreneur prepares how his product will be viewed in front of the world, and when it is viewed, how easily the entrepreneur manages the interactions necessary for a successful crowdfunding deal. Even though one might feel that pre-crowdfunding might not entail a lot of work, it is actually the infrastructure setting stage that determines all the success that follows if the business idea is appealing. There are several things that need to be perfected in this stage. Firstly, The entrepreneur needs to <a href="http://www.crowdfunding-website-reviews.com/pre-crowdfunding/">perfect his elevator pitch</a>. He needs to be able to successfully communicate his business idea in two minutes. He needs to verify this by explaining the concept to a kid who has no concept of business. By doing so, the entrepreneur ensures that his method of explaining is both efficient and easy to comprehend. He or she needs to work on their speaking skills including how fast they speak and their accent. Sometimes the entrepreneurs do not belong to the local area, and so they need to work as much as possible to make sure that listeners can understand them without much difficulty. Once the elevator pitch is down, the entrepreneurs can cross off the first and the most important task of the pre-crowdfunding. Having an excellent elevator pitch means that people are drawn to you. They sense your passion and are willing to know more about you and your business idea.\r\n\r\nBut introducing your idea and yourself successfully is not the only thing that happens during the crowdfunding stage. The next most important thing an entrepreneur should prepare for in the pre-crowdfunding stage is the <a href="https://www.crowdfunder.com/blog/knowledge-center/how-to-build-an-equity-crowdfunding-campaign/">crowdfunding campaign</a>. It is extremely important to sustain the crowdfunding buzz once the word is out through your elevator pitch. An example of a most successful crowdfunding campaign to date is of Star Citizen, an online space combat video game. This project alone has raised more than <a href="https://robertsspaceindustries.com/funding-goals">$80 million</a>, which is the highest reported funding to date. In order to get maximum amount of funds, the campaign needs to be global. This depends in part on your goals and vision, and on your application or audience of the business idea. If the entrepreneur seeks global distribution, then his campaign needs be organized in such a manner. Building a website, making interactive videos about the concept and connecting through various social media platforms such as Facebook, twitter, LinkedIn, Google plus, Pinterest, Tumblr, Instagram and others goes a long way in maintaining a truly global presence. The entrepreneur can also seek to come on radio as well as digital broadcasting networks including YouTube to have a wide scale impact. While a lot of the campaigning ideas need money, the entrepreneur can take comfort that he can allocate the spending of the campaign from crowdfunding money. This would necessitate carefully planning of the budget and expenses, which is why we believe pre-crowdfunding goes a long way in determining success for entrepreneurs.\r\n\r\nFinally, we believe that in order for an entrepreneur to be really successful in their crowdfunding process, they need to ponder whether they need any advisors to facilitate the business. The entrepreneurs can ask themselves whether they are seeking capital from someone in particular who along with their investment will provide strategic and technical advice needed for the business. The entrepreneurs also need to be efficient in their paper work, documentation, compiling of basic corporate information, regulatory documents and they must have their business banking account issue resolved. The entrepreneur can choose to go PayPal or use an escrow account offered by the equity crowdfunding portal, but in either case the process after the investor has signed the deal needs to be planned out in advance of the crowdfunding process itself.', 'What is pre-crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 19:17:51', '2015-05-11 19:17:51', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=743', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(744, 10, '2015-05-12 03:47:13', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX believe that the modern era of investment through equity crowdfunding is here. Gone are\r\n\r\nthose days when the business deals were accessible only to a few privileged class of people. Today, the\r\n\r\ndemocratization of investment has taken its tangible form, and the reality is that anybody can invest or seek\r\n\r\ninvestment. This has obviously been a tremendous feat, and while there is a long way to go through proper\r\n\r\nregulatory policies to protect and make sure the system evolves in the positive direction, we have a lot to be\r\n\r\nthankful about, and we need to capitalize the opportunities available to us today than ever before. Today, there\r\n\r\nare more than 500 equity crowdfunding portals around the world. Equity crowdfunding portals are the baseline\r\n\r\ninfrastructure that has facilitated the building of an ecosystem that nurtures everybody involved in the business.\r\n\r\nTo understand how exactly the process of equity crowdfunding works, we need to first look at this phenomenon\r\n\r\nin terms of duties and responsibilities of two main parties involved in the process, i-e. the investor, the party\r\n\r\nwho is interested in lending money in return for equity or share in the company, and the issuer, the party also\r\n\r\nreferred as the entrepreneur, or the owner of the emerging business or startup. As discussed above, in order for\r\n\r\nan equity crowdfunding deal to take place, we need an equity crowdfunding portal, for example like the one we\r\n\r\nhave made called eco-system infrastructure platform (ESIP). Through our platform, you will be facilitated\r\n\r\nthrough out your investment during different phases such as pre-during-post crowdfunding transactions. Our\r\n\r\nequity portal will help you by maintaining due diligence of issuers, data repository or deal room, and will also\r\n\r\nhelp in shareholder management and communications, something that is quite revolutionary in today’s modern\r\n\r\nworld of transparency. Finally, for every type of investor, whether you are a CEO, a lawyer, auditor or even a\r\n\r\nthird party provider, we have provide a safe and secured platform with a single point of entry to prevent an\r\n\r\nleakage and mishandling of corporate or personal information.\r\n\r\nTo start the process of equity crowdfunding, both the investor and the entrepreneur first need to make an\r\n\r\naccount on the website of the equity crowdfunding portal they wish to use for their business. While the\r\n\r\nentrepreneur can easily choose an equity crowdfunding portal based on the business he seeks to promote, the\r\n\r\ninvestor can only select an equity crowdfunding portal based on his status as an accredited or non-accredited\r\n\r\ninvestor. Accredited investors also known as sophisticated investors are those individuals who are accredited by\r\n\r\nthe securities commission (local government) to carry high net worth (around more than $1 million) and are\r\n\r\nsafe from majorly impacting their finances in case the equity crowdfunding deal crashes. Non-accredited\r\n\r\ninvestors on the contrary are the remaining people who do not meet the requirements of accreditation. While\r\n\r\nthis may be seen has an hindrance for an ordinary citizen, the requirement for being an accredited investor by\r\n\r\nmany equity crowdfunding portals is placed to ensure safety of the parties involved. Once the account has been\r\n\r\nmade, the entrepreneur is contacted by the equity crowdfunding portal to provide corporate information that\r\n\r\nallows the portal to conduct efficient and stringent process of due diligence. Even if it is not required, if the\r\n\r\nentrepreneur prepares himself as if he were to go through due diligence, this step would place the entrepreneur\r\n\r\nin a much more stable position because he would have to show the basic corporate information to other\r\n\r\ninterested parties later anyways. Once all the due diligence information is uploaded on the portal, the equity\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding portal team review the information provided to decide whether the emerging business would be\r\n\r\nlisted on the portal website. This is normally conducted by the team’s compliance officer. Once the entrepreneur\r\n\r\nis approved, the entrepreneur then provides his business plan, financial statements, shareholders agreement and\r\n\r\nother important information to be displayed for interested investors on the portal website. Once on display,\r\n\r\ninvestors review the information provided and decide whether they would like to invest in the emerging\r\n\r\nbusiness. If the investor is interested, the equity crowdfunding portal team decides whether the investor is\r\n\r\neligible for investment, and if the investor does pass this stage, the investor signs final documents online to seal\r\n\r\nthe deal.\r\n\r\nTo conclude the deal and equity crowdfunding process, the investor simply transfers the funds to an escrow\r\n\r\naccount, and if the right amount of funds are raised by the entrepreneur, the entrepreneur stops raising money,\r\n\r\nand gets the funds from an escrow account. In this process, the equity crowdfunding portal charges some fees\r\n\r\nfor the work they put into confirming the deal. Once the final amount is sent, the investors now become\r\n\r\nshareholders, and the portal manages the communications and future dealings among themselves and the\r\n\r\nentrepreneur. The portal also sends final documents to shareholders to confirm their investment, and the number\r\n\r\nof shares they posses. Finally, the entrepreneur sends all regulatory reports after the transaction has been\r\n\r\ncompleted.', 'What is the process for equity crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:47:13', '2015-05-12 03:47:13', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=744', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(745, 10, '2015-05-12 03:47:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'One of the key goals of KoreConX is to adequately inform businesses owners where the lingo\r\n\r\nsurrounding equity crowdfunding is concerned. For these purposes, we’ve created our “Fundamental\r\n\r\nDefinitions” series, which seeks to keep you up to speed with the kinds of terms you’ll be interacting\r\n\r\nwith upon entering the equity crowdfunding space.\r\n\r\nWhen discussing business in general, you’ll frequently hear the terms “B2B”, “B2C”, and “P2P”, among\r\n\r\nothers. What do these four three-character terms mean, though? Most generally speaking, they refer to\r\n\r\nthe many kinds of transactions that can occur in the business world!\r\n\r\nBusiness-to-business (B2B) transactions are commercial transactions that, as their name suggests, occur\r\n\r\nbetween two businesses. As an example, transactions often occur between a manufacturer (someone\r\n\r\nwho produces goods) and a wholesaler (someone who sells them en masse), and, further down the line,\r\n\r\nbetween the aforementioned wholesaler and, say, an independent retailer. Overall, the volume of\r\n\r\nbusiness-to-business (B2B) transactions occurring within the world is much higher than the volume of\r\n\r\nbusiness-to-consumer transactions occurring. This makes sense, considering our example: note that\r\n\r\nthree businesses had to interact to get the product to the customer, but only one business actually\r\n\r\ninteracted with a customer: in other words, there were two B2B transactions here, but one only B2C\r\n\r\ntransaction. “B2B communication” can also refer to communication between two employees\r\n\r\nfunctioning within one business; a lot of software and many other technologies, for example, are now\r\n\r\nbeing created to ameliorate B2B communication within businesses (i.e., to improve how employees\r\n\r\nwork together, for example).\r\n\r\nBusiness-to-consumer (B2C) transactions, by contrast, involve transactions between organizations and\r\n\r\nconsumers. For the most part, this means retail: the process of settling goods and services to customers,\r\n\r\nwhich can occur through multiple distribution channels. Retailing can be done via individual shops,\r\n\r\nshopping malls, or via non-shop retailing (e.g., online retailing, or retailing via mail order).\r\n\r\nPeer-to-peer (P2P) transactions are yet another kind of communication and networking that can occur\r\n\r\nbetween two entities. As the name implies, this involves a transaction between two equally privileged,\r\n\r\nequipotent participants. In the case of businesses, this involves matching borrowers with lenders where\r\n\r\nentities lend money to another entity in return for repayment of the principal loan plus some interest.\r\n\r\nP2P has its own portals, and because it is considered a security under Canadian law, P2P lenders are\r\n\r\ninvestors. While P2P lending is considered a kind of equity crowdfunding, it stands counter to equity\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding platforms in that it is not expressly permitted to occur online under Canadian legislation.\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, many different kinds of transactions exist; understanding them and the parties they\r\n\r\ninvolve can be very useful in deciphering day-to-day business lingo!', 'Fundamental Definitions: B2B, B2C, and P2P', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:47:35', '2015-05-12 03:47:35', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=745', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(746, 10, '2015-05-12 03:47:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In past articles, we’ve already spoken of the fact that equity crowdfunding is quickly growing to be an\r\n\r\ninternational phenomenon. Now, let’s examine specifically how equity crowdfunding pertains to the life\r\n\r\nsciences, and think about how professionals and organizations in life-science-centered research,\r\n\r\nacademia, industry, and health care can benefit from engaging in equity crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nAt present, it has been argued that crowdfunding is one of the most powerful ways of connecting\r\n\r\nscience and society, mostly because the amount of money one generates via crowdfunding is directly\r\n\r\nindicative of the size of one’s audience, and thus reveals how thoroughly a researcher’s science is\r\n\r\ngaining credibility with the general populace. Via equity crowdfunding, scientists may be able to share\r\n\r\ntheir work and their philosophies with many thousands of people per year, and if these people become\r\n\r\nsufficiently interested in the work being done, they can influence policy-making decisions at the\r\n\r\ngovernment level. Further, equity crowdfunding “science projects” don’t just help disseminate an\r\n\r\nawareness of and appreciation for science – they may also assist everyday people in becoming more\r\n\r\nfamiliar with health science and, by extension, in becoming more actively involved in maintaining their\r\n\r\nown health.\r\n\r\nScientific and healthcare charities can also benefit immensely from crowdfunding. Cancer Research UK,\r\n\r\nfor example, has routinely raised more than fifty thousand pounds for projects just via crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nTarget Cancer, in the USA, has also worked to combat rare cancers via research, seed funding for young\r\n\r\nresearchers, and collaboration-building among researchers. Countless other life sciences groups have\r\n\r\nbenefited from crowdfunding, among them The Immunity Project (a non-profit scientific research group\r\n\r\nworking towards developing a synthetic HIV/AIDS vaccine, which has received funding and help from\r\n\r\nFlow Pharma, SparkArt, “Until There’s a Cure”, the famed Y Combinator, Crowdhoster, and even\r\n\r\nMicrosoft).\r\n\r\nIt is clear, then, that crowdfunding can be of benefit to life sciences group. But which groups precisely,\r\n\r\nand what should interested life sciences organizations have prepared for crowdfunding?\r\n\r\nTo begin with, some life sciences projects are more suitable for crowdfunding than others. Specifically,\r\n\r\nthe most successful life science crowdfunding projects tend to be those that can appeal to an audience\r\n\r\nwith a motivation. To be more specific, while angels tend to invest predominantly for financial gains,\r\n\r\nthose operating in the healthcare sphere will often also consider just how thoroughly the public needs a\r\n\r\ngiven project. Further, everyday people – some of whom may contribute to crowdfunding – are also\r\n\r\nmore likely to invest in projects whose causes are close to their hearts – people with cancer-ridden\r\n\r\nrelatives may, for example, be more prone to contribute to related crowdfunding projects. As such,\r\n\r\naccording to both Gonҫalo de Vasconcelos (from Syndicateroom) and Jason Corum (from BIOtechNOW)\r\n\r\nagree that those life sciences projects most suitable for crowdfunding are those with a strongly\r\n\r\nmotivational cause.\r\n\r\nConversely, some life sciences projects are less than fitting for crowdfunding. Drug discovery, for\r\n\r\nexample, because it tends to require a lot of funding and take an abundance of time to see results, is not\r\n\r\nbest serviced by crowdfunding campaigns. Issues of due diligence, IP concerns, and the problems\r\n\r\nassociated with having too many shareholders are all responsible for most life sciences executives’\r\n\r\nthinking that drug discovery and crowdfunding just don’t mesh, unless the companies involved are very\r\n\r\nearly-stage.\r\n\r\nAssuming you’re a group that thinks it can benefit from engaging in crowdfunding on the basis of the\r\n\r\nabove notes, it’s also important to consider a few benefits and risks to crowdfunding that are relevant to\r\n\r\nthe life sciences. Crowdfunding can be beneficial for a few reasons. It can help project organizers raise\r\n\r\ntheir reputation outside of academia. It can help show investors that there is demand for a given\r\n\r\ncampaign. It can also allow project initiators to more actively engage with their audiences, and learn\r\n\r\nfrom them during and after the crowdfunding process. Project initiators can also more easily engage in\r\n\r\nmarket testing if they are involved in crowdfunding, can learn from people accustomed to investing, can\r\n\r\nempower and educate the public, and can initiate scientific conversation in the media. However,\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding can also be problematic for life sciences groups. Namely, if a group fails to reach a\r\n\r\ncampaign goal, cannot obtain public support, or fails to deliver a desired result, its reputation may fall,\r\n\r\nand public understanding of science’s efficacy may be modified. Further, publicly announcing the details\r\n\r\nof a project before production occurs can lead to intellectual property theft. As mentioned in prior\r\n\r\narticles, equity crowdfunding, in many countries, also lacks the regulatory framework needed to\r\n\r\nguarantee that abuse of funds does not occur; lack of due diligence is also a pressing concern, given that\r\n\r\nnon-scientists often donate without conducting their own prior research, and may thus be swept up in\r\n\r\ncontributing to unsound projects. Managing communications becomes tough with many investors and\r\n\r\nsupporters, and fostering such communication can even divert funds from the project itself.\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, while crowdfunding is a great tool for life sciences companies, be they in research,\r\n\r\nhealthcare, academia, or industry, careful consideration is needed prior to diving headfirst into this\r\n\r\nsphere.', 'Industry Focus: Equity Crowdfunding in the Life Sciences', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:47:51', '2015-05-12 03:47:51', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=746', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(747, 10, '2015-05-12 03:48:08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a previous article, we discussed crowdfunding – and, in particular, equity crowdfunding – and its\r\n\r\nimpact on the life sciences industry. In today’s KoreConX article, we’ll explore just how beneficial equity\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding can be to those operating in oil and gas, and how oil and gas organizations should go\r\n\r\nabout preparing to enter the sphere of equity crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nTo begin, equity crowdfunding has now decidedly entered oil and gas – to the extent, in fact, that some\r\n\r\nhave called crowdfunding “the future of oil”. People looking to invest in oil and gas can now crowdfund\r\n\r\nonline; on EnergyFunders.com, for example, one can buy a piece of a small oil well project and get back\r\n\r\na piece of the revenue. Philip Racusin, CEO of the aforementioned company, cites equity crowdfunding\r\n\r\nas a tremendously effective way to get involved in oil: when wells produce, he says, and you purchase a\r\n\r\nbit of them via crowdfunding, “you’re getting revenue directly from the well, without having to pay for\r\n\r\nexpensive overhead” – an advantage unique to this kind of purchasing, despite the risks. For everyday\r\n\r\ncitizens, there’s another advantage to equity crowdfunding in gas and oil: while investments typically\r\n\r\ninvolve around $100 000 in oil and gas via traditional investment methods, people can buy in to oil via\r\n\r\nEnergyFunders.com for as little as $3500 to $5000. This means that oil will be “democratized for\r\n\r\neveryone”, as Racusin puts it – at least, when federal securities law finally opens the floor to non-\r\n\r\naccredited investors.\r\n\r\nIn all fairness, however, it must be noted: oil and gas is incredibly new to the equity crowdfunding space,\r\n\r\nand not everybody believes the industry will actually embrace crowdfunding as anything more than a\r\n\r\nniche product. Many traditional energy lenders and finance experts say they’re concerned that\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding – while compelling in its novelty – may not become a stable funding source for oil and gas\r\n\r\ngroups. Christopher Ross, for example, a former BP Plc executive, suggests that directly investing in oil\r\n\r\nand gas is problematic, because would-be investors are probably going to be unfamiliar with the\r\n\r\ntechnology, geology, and mineral-related financing surrounding energy acquisitions. While this could be\r\n\r\nof concern to investors, there is some hope – sites like EnergyFunder tend to equip buyers with heaps of\r\n\r\ndata about projects, including lease information and seismic data. From the point of view of an oil and\r\n\r\ngas company, further, it seems that equity crowdfunding really does have the potential to be helpful –\r\n\r\nearly this January, for example, EnergyFunders raised more than $200 000 in six days: enough to\r\n\r\ncompletely cover a specific sixteen-well oil project. A rival company, CrudeFunders, agrees that now is a\r\n\r\n“great time to invest in oil”, too, as there’s been a drop in oil prices that makes oil and gas – a\r\n\r\nnotoriously volatile commodity – accessible to individuals now more so than previously.\r\n\r\nSo, what does an oil and gas company need to have prepared for equity crowdfunding, assuming that\r\n\r\nentering the sphere is a move of interest? Well, not too much! Operators need only have a good\r\n\r\nreputation, some information on wells they have drilled in the past, and an oil or gas project that they\r\n\r\nare interested in having funded. A site like EnergyFunders screens operators for reputability; approved\r\n\r\noperators are subsequently allowed to upload projects to the site, where accredited investors may then\r\n\r\ncontribute to the project.\r\n\r\nWhy should operators utilize sites like EnergyFunders? According to CrowdFundBeat, there are a few\r\n\r\nreasons. For one, equity crowdfunding has already proven itself as a method of generating large\r\n\r\nquantities of money (albeit that, as described above, some may think its future in oil and gas to be a bit\r\n\r\nhazy). Further, however, financing is free for oil and gas operators on EnergyFunders, and the site allows\r\n\r\noperators preferential rights to purchase when it divests a once-productive well. Finally, an operator\r\n\r\nworking with EnergyFunders is able to working with one interest owner as opposed to many.', 'Industry Focus: Equity Crowdfunding in Oil and Gas', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:48:08', '2015-05-12 03:48:08', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=747', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(748, 10, '2015-05-12 03:48:32', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In previous articles, we explored how equity crowdfunding pertains to the life sciences, as well as to oil\r\n\r\nand gas; cumulatively, we found that this novel phenomenon can be utilized to enhance projects being\r\n\r\ncarried out in both industries, provided that the projects and people involved are well-equipped to\r\n\r\nparticipate in equity crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nMining, like oil and gas, seems like a bizarre industry within which to find equity crowdfunding, but it\r\n\r\nseems that crowdfunding has penetrated the industry to a considerable extent as of late. While\r\n\r\ntechnology venture-capital and other industries have their own crowdfunding portals, the mining world\r\n\r\nhas yet to see its own crowdfunding tool; for the most part, entrepreneurs in the area have been more\r\n\r\nactive via public venture capital exchanges like the TSXV and the CSE.\r\n\r\nAs such, it’s understandable that investors and issuers have long been searching for alternative\r\n\r\nfinancing, and KlondikeStrike aims to be the first mining-centric solution, in this regard – as expected,\r\n\r\ngiven our subject matter, this company is focused on creating the first mining-centered equity\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding portal. The group, replete with mining experts, aims to bring forward a wide variety of\r\n\r\ninvestments and multiple commodities in order to catalyze investor interest. Its CEO, Chad Williams,\r\n\r\nhimself a mining analyst of fifteen years, believes that equity crowdfunding can “completely transform\r\n\r\nthe way mining companies raise money”. What’s more, this project is offering its securities through\r\n\r\nexemptions made available in National Instrument 45-106 Prospectus and Registration Exemptions, and\r\n\r\nall the company’s activities are being conducted in compliance with the relevant securities regulations.\r\n\r\nThis kind of solution comes at a particularly useful time for mining. The world’s mining industry hasn’t\r\n\r\nbeen doing as well as it once did, most dominantly because several fundamental factors have meant\r\n\r\nthat the prices of precious metals are now more problematic than ever. BullionVault, for example,\r\n\r\nreported that metal prices have lost about one-third of their values now, as compared to the 2010 to\r\n\r\n2012 period. This is exacerbated by the fact that mining, what with its unsafe working conditions,\r\n\r\nproblematic environmental impact, and licensing difficulties, is far from an investor favorite to begin\r\n\r\nwith. Fortunately for the industry, crowdfunding appears to have the resources to change this situation\r\n\r\naround: by forcing companies to be transparent about their working operations and financial\r\n\r\nstatements, crowdfunding helps ensure that potential investors are able to see which mining companies\r\n\r\nseem to be high-quality future earners; this, in turn, drives investment into the right industry players –\r\n\r\nthe ones who have nothing to hide. KlondikeStrike is already showing this to be true: a company called\r\n\r\nPlanetary Resources – centered on mining asteroids for precious metals and other resources – has\r\n\r\nalready been able to profit greatly from crowdfunding, raising over one million dollars in just thirty days.\r\n\r\nThis is promising, particularly because the mining industry – while it isn’t doing so well in developed\r\n\r\nregions – has tremendous growth potential in the developing world. Natural resources like minerals and\r\n\r\nmetals are used in almost all the major sectors of a country’s economy, so as a country’s urbanization\r\n\r\nclimbs, demand for minerals increases, too. India, Brazil, and China, for example, have reached the level\r\n\r\nof urbanization necessary (about thirty percent) to elevate mineral demand by about 5000 to 10 000\r\n\r\ndollars per annum in recent years; as such, the mining sector in these regions has experienced\r\n\r\nsubstantial growth. Given that equity crowdfunding is also taking hold in regions like these, it seems\r\n\r\nunderstandable that equity crowdfunding portals geared explicitly at mining could successfully raise\r\n\r\nsignificant capital.\r\n\r\nIf you’re interested in getting involved in mining-related equity crowdfunding right now, a few portals –\r\n\r\nboth mining-exclusive and others – already exist. As mentioned, there’s Canada’s KlondikeStrike; the\r\n\r\nUSA has truCrowd Texas in Houston, and the UK has VentureFounders in London.', 'Industry Focus: Equity Crowdfunding in Mining', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:48:32', '2015-05-12 03:48:32', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=748', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(749, 10, '2015-05-12 03:49:08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a prior article series called “Equity Crowdfunding around the World”, we toured North America, Latin\r\n\r\nAmerica, Asia, Oceania, and Europe to find out how equity crowdfunding was faring in different locales;\r\n\r\nas you may remember, upon carefully considering Canada, we noted that Canada’s a great place to be\r\n\r\nwhen it comes to equity crowdfunding, whether you’re a portal, an investor, or an entrepreneur. Today,\r\n\r\nwe’ll focus further on just how to engage in equity crowdfunding in Canada; specifically, we’ll look into\r\n\r\nwhere you can equity crowdfund if you’re a Canadian company or entrepreneur looking to raise some\r\n\r\ncapital.\r\n\r\nAs I’ve mentioned before, I think it’s important to state that, before you venture further into equity\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding, you should take the time out to find out if it’s right for you. This can be done via, for\r\n\r\nexample, the website of the National Crowdfunding Association of Canada (NCFA), which lays out\r\n\r\nimportant questions for entrepreneurs to consider prior to entering the space. Not all types of\r\n\r\nbusinesses can crowdfund in Canada – it’s important to know which securities exemption you fall under\r\n\r\nbefore you can decide whether or not you can create an equity crowdfunding campaign. Further, just\r\n\r\nhow much a business is allowed to raise also depends upon which securities law exemption it will be\r\n\r\nrelying on during the campaign. Finally, equity crowdfunding may not necessarily be the right form of\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding for your group, else crowdfunding in general may not be the best way for you to raise\r\n\r\ncapital.\r\n\r\nAssuming, however, that you are a Canadian company thoroughly committed to equity crowdfunding,\r\n\r\nthere are several different portals that you can utilize in order to equity crowdfund. While\r\n\r\ncomprehensive lists exist spanning both equity and other kinds of crowdfunding, we will stick to the\r\n\r\nformer here.\r\n\r\nWithout further ado, a list of equity crowdfunding portals in Canada:\r\n\r\n CloudFund: Based in Alberta, this equity portal seeks to back Canadian start-ups of all kinds\r\n\r\n CrowdFuel: Another portal centered on start-up fundraising, based in Saskatchewan; this one\r\n\r\nalso accommodates debt-based crowdfunding\r\n\r\n CrowdMatrix: An Ontario-based site, CrowdMatrix is limited to accredited investors, and again\r\n\r\nseeks to back start-up fundraising without charging companies and investors transaction fees\r\n\r\n Fundica: A Quebec-based site delivering crowdsourced access to grants, tax credits, loans, and\r\n\r\nequity funding, as well\r\n\r\n InvestX: Famed for its entry into mining, BC-based InvestX offers private equity for investors\r\n\r\n MetroFunder: Another BC-based equity crowdfunding site, this one centered mostly on real\r\n\r\nestate\r\n\r\n NexusCrowd: An Ontario-based site for accredited investors only\r\n\r\n Open Avenue: An Ontario-based site, again focused dominantly on real estate\r\n\r\n Optimize Capital Markets: A site offering private placements for accredited investors and\r\n\r\ninstitutions, Optimize Capital Markets is another equity crowdfunding portal based in Ontario\r\n\r\n Podium Ventures: An Alberta-based site focused exclusively on pairing high-tech start-ups with\r\n\r\naccredited investors via equity crowdfunding\r\n\r\n SeedUps Canada: A well-known, Alberta-based equity crowdfunding portal\r\n\r\n Silver Maple Ventures: Based in BC\r\n\r\n SVX: Based in Ontario, and focused largely on social venture exchange for impact ventures,\r\n\r\nfunds, and investors\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, many Canadian options exist where equity crowdfunding is concerned! We’re also\r\n\r\nincredibly fortunate to have an abundance of information available to us here in Canada. If you’re an\r\n\r\nentrepreneur looking to enter the equity crowdfunding space in Canada, the National Crowdfunding\r\n\r\nAssociation of Canada (NCFA) is a great place to get the research, information, events, leadership, and\r\n\r\nnetworking you need to get involved in the Canadian arena. With record-breaking campaigns hitting the\r\n\r\nnation, and events like the Canadian Crowdfunding Summit spreading awareness, now’s a great time to\r\n\r\nbe in Canadian crowdfunding, particularly if you’re an innovative entrepreneur!', 'Common Questions: I am a Canadian company, where can I equity crowdfund?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 03:49:08', '2015-05-12 03:49:08', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=749', 0, 'post', '', 0);
