(750, 10, '2015-05-12 22:24:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a prior article series – namely, the “Equity Crowdfunding around the World” group of articles – we toured North America, Latin America, Asia, Europe, and Oceania in trying to examine just how global a phenomenon crowdfunding is. As part of that series, too, we managed to establish that the USA is really a hub where equity crowdfunding is concerned, and that investors, entrepreneurs, and portals alike have much to gain from operating in the USA. In another past article, we also considered just how American investors can profit from the entrepreneurial culture and equity crowdfunding boom characteristic to the States. Here, we’ll take a slightly different perspective. If you’re an American company or an American entrepreneur, where precisely can you equity crowdfund, within the States? To what resources can you turn?\r\n\r\nAs it stands, though the US only legalized the equity crowdfunding landscape last year, it has already seen the inception of over 1000 websites dedicated to this phenomenon. Equity crowdfunding in this country is expected to grow even further in 2015, for up to $17 billion! Further, not all US platforms require that people be accredited investors, which creates an even more flexible equity crowdfunding arena than one can find in many other locales.\r\n\r\nHere, then, is a short list of equity crowdfunding platforms in the US via which you can broadcast your projects, whether you’re a company or an individual:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fangel.co%2F&amp;ei=XSE9VYi2E7DdsATbzoH4DA&amp;usg=AFQjCNG07Amw4_R3yedobbYoJNxKqpcaGw&amp;sig2=cC0NpjUFEnMwX0waGxmWYQ&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">AngelList</a>: Specifically for accredited investors: only accredit investors can invest, at the moment, while start-ups can utilize this site to raise equity or debt for their work! AngelList can also be utilize for recruitment and job-searching!</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fcircleup.com%2F&amp;ei=gyE9VZTyG4rmsATYmICwDQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNG0joLuK4FU07n2-SDf0ijhiWXLoQ&amp;sig2=5j8ImQ6x6ZLltmPGjeKzrw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">CircleUp</a>: A US site with several success investment stories to its name, with allows investors to communicate directly with CEOs, possess access to all financials and diligence documents, work with both consumer and retail investors, and invest directly into companies of their choice! Entrepreneurs, on the other hand, have the benefits of working with partners like General Mills, P&amp;G, and SPINs via CircleUp’s connections, and can utilize innovative online tools to manage investor relations!</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCAQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.earlyshares.com%2F&amp;ei=kiE9VcifHuLLsAT034CYBw&amp;usg=AFQjCNG9lZBbjRxNnHF4TNrYWLZak-Tu8w&amp;sig2=xeSMCx3V1WSYf2pQri_r_Q&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Early Shares</a>: A site that gives accredited US investors direct access to private opportunities in real estate and investment funds; thousands of investors, presumably, frequent the site, with potential for more than $200 million to be invested in the next twelve months! This site is particularly selective, accepting fewer than 5% of applicants!</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCkQFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.equitynet.com%2F&amp;ei=niE9VaWDPLHmsATT8oCQAg&amp;usg=AFQjCNEQwPyzqFmqiQjfUoI-Li8m2HE38w&amp;sig2=rq1OWfbucEduHKIsvS-Whg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">EquityNet</a>: Open to all investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fundable.com%2F&amp;ei=rCE9VY3MFfOIsQS4wYDwDA&amp;usg=AFQjCNH7YfJxcp-qeioDqEce0_15nTNh-Q&amp;sig2=X2bp_QRbVPK1lqTpqUD86g&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Fundable</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Ffundersclub.com%2F&amp;ei=tyE9VZrNK-ewsASfzYDQCQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNHsWRJpSA4lqciMkg0BOU2Kl6qIPQ&amp;sig2=LPh0QYJqFzB2datCYX6L8w&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">FundersClub</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gofundme.com%2F&amp;ei=wiE9Vbe1GZTasASYw4C4Cg&amp;usg=AFQjCNF2Y3v9Xh3dW90mqt_jWXSkhoq_QA&amp;sig2=pfdbbzcYa9_yBSDKg0P32Q&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">GoFundMe</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCgQFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.investedin.com%2F&amp;ei=zSE9VcHHEJLIsQSooIDoAQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNFBUdGjSv4ss0mmmTHp5wZ_wOd-KQ&amp;sig2=LtUebXaD_add4Uj2Vle9Jg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Investedin</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CC8QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lendingclub.com%2F&amp;ei=4iE9VbuROaTHsQSg2oDACw&amp;usg=AFQjCNGJab0rLwlxcqtrgGNcYykayTDyhw&amp;sig2=nwIb-60V7G-b8mHY3HvqaA&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Lending Club</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCkQFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fmicroventures.com%2F&amp;ei=8CE9Vai7B6HLsAS2poDwCw&amp;usg=AFQjCNFoXSiyIkVOLmJ2ZmTuprDuOog1tw&amp;sig2=RdkJxNIAUTZfgQSUgboNPg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">MicroVentures</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.seedinvest.com%2F&amp;ei=AyI9VYW5K4LfsASvtIHACw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEz3pNHfsDEPVGWp7cIajG-1zI5tQ&amp;sig2=j8PGtP9E-CsWnoeMgP50qw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">SeedInvest</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.startupvalley.com%2F&amp;ei=EiI9VZLjMbK1sATVkYGIDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNG-5HYBQswdb18FlLNsnoTKzcP9Ew&amp;sig2=mN5vurb-OfsnfkI1tS5WMw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">StartupValley</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCgQFjAB&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.upstart.com%2F&amp;ei=ISI9VZKFBLiIsQT1woCYDg&amp;usg=AFQjCNGMBG61yDpywtbRhX3Z_R6lOw05Rw&amp;sig2=MMPicrU05BzNLx-tCpvwVg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Upstart</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=4&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CDcQFjAD&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.crunchbase.com%2Forganization%2Frock-the-post&amp;ei=NSI9VcSHFYLisATHqYCABA&amp;usg=AFQjCNF0BBqCyAROw0BhNSXatjhikY_nKA&amp;sig2=frsQhXVnA5r3LQxXSdRZaA&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">RockThePost</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt’s also important to note that there are many vertical portals (“vortals”) not listed above. Vortals are portals dedicated to a particular industry (<em>e.g.</em>, health care, insurance, food manufacturing). These are, in other words, portals to vertical industries, which are industries focused on a relatively narrow range of goods and services (horizontal industries, by contrast, produce a broader range of goods and services). Vertical portals are relevant to equity crowdfunding because most industries tend to specialize, and thus, tend to be vertical. Vertical portals can thus serve to unite people interested in buying, selling, or exchanging information about a specific subset of topics and products. As such, if you’re an entrepreneur with a specific focus (<em>e.g.</em>, music, visual arts/creative projects, social projects, student support projects, sports, journalism, product design, furniture, fashion), you should be able to find even more sites specifically catered to your purposes. For a good list of them, go <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">here</a>.\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, there are many, many portals you can utilize if you’re an American company or entrepreneur looking to engage in equity crowdfunding.', 'Common Questions: I am an American company, where can I equity crowdfund?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 22:24:51', '2015-05-12 22:24:51', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=750', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(751, 10, '2015-05-12 22:25:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'At KoreConX, one of our major goals is to familiarize you with the business and finance terminology that surrounds crowdfunding, and equity crowdfunding in particular. As such, because we have utilized this term in several past articles without explanation, we thought we should dedicate a single article to laying out who precisely an “accredited investor” is, and why being an accredited investor is different from being an unaccredited investor when it comes to equity crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nTo begin, who qualifies as an accredited investor differs largely on the basis of your region. In Canada, however, an accredited investor is an individual who meets any of the following <a href="http://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/21943.htm/">criteria</a>:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>An individual who, either alone or together with his or her spouse, owns assets worth more than one million dollars before tax, or an individual who, together with a spouse or alone, has net assets of minimally five million dollars</li>\r\n	<li>An individual whose net income has been more than $200 000 before tax in both of the last two years, and who expects to maintain that kind of income this coming year</li>\r\n	<li>An individual whose net income, combined with the net income of his or her spouse, has been more than $300 000 in both of the last two years, and who expects to maintain that kind of income this coming year</li>\r\n	<li>An individual who is currently or once was a registered adviser or a dealer, other than a limited market dealer</li>\r\n	<li>Financial institutions, governmental agencies and governments, insurance companies, pension funds, registered charities, certain mutual funds, pooled funds, managed accounts, companies with minimally five million dollars of net assets, and people or groups recognized by the OSC as accredited investors can also be considered accredited investors</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSimilarly, in the United States, for an individual to be considered accredited, he or she must have a net worth of at least one million USD, not including the value of their primary residence, or have an income of at least $200 000 in both of the last two years (or $300 000 together with his or her spouse) and expect to make the same amount this year. Banks, insurance companies, registered investment companies, business development companies, or small investment companies, as well as employee benefit plans, charitable organizations, corporations, or partnerships with assets exceeding five million dollars, a trust with assets in excess of five million, and several other groups are all accredited investors, by the USA definition. Still different criteria for accreditation exist in the EU, Australia, New Zealand, and other locales where crowdfunding is currently rapidly taking over.\r\n\r\nWhy is it important to be an accredited investor, however? What relevance does this have to equity crowdfunding, both from the entrepreneur and portal’s standpoint and from the investor’s?\r\n\r\nWell, for entrepreneurs, working with an accredited investor means that you can use the accredited investor exemption – legislature that allows you to raise any amount at any time from a person or company who qualifies as an accredited investor. The law assumes that accredited investors don’t need the protection of a prospectus, because they have enough money at their disposal to handle the loss of their entire investment, should things go wrong, and because they have the business acumen, presumably, to analyze the information needed to intelligently assess an investment without a prospectus. As such, this means that, as long as an accredited investor is purchasing securities for himself or herself, he or she can, effectively, buy as much as he or she wants. This is, obviously, favorable for the entrepreneur, who can make a considerable amount of money off of working with such investors.\r\n\r\nFor the equity crowdfunding portal handling the entrepreneur-investor transaction, working with accredited investors is also beneficial, in a sense: by only allowing highly qualified and reputable investors to participate via your portal, you mitigate the risk of having to deal with unhappy entrepreneurs, and may even increase your reputation by increasing the amount of capital raised for your projects. The downside, of course, is that only permitting accredited investors to invest makes for a smaller investor pool.\r\n\r\nIf you’re an accredited investor yourself, too, you’re in luck! Many portals, at the moment, cater exclusively to accredited investors; as such, for you, the opportunities in equity crowdfunding have very few limitations! Just ensure that you align with your country’s criteria for accreditation, and you should be good to go!', 'Fundamental Definitions: Accredited Investors', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 22:25:21', '2015-05-12 22:25:21', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=751', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(752, 10, '2015-05-12 22:25:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'The world of equity crowdfunding is here! It is a system of highly integrated, standardized and automated processes that ensure that financial investments are done in a way that was never possible before. Although there has been much talk about lack of robustness in legislation, there has been swift progress in terms of equity crowdfunding portals around the world. As of 2013, there were more than <a href="http://www.equities.com/editors-desk/crowd-investing/crowdfunding/6-equity-crowdfunding-opportunities-for-investors-and-consumers">500 such portals</a>, <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/ryancaldbeck/2012/12/11/crowdfunding-predictions-for-2013/">60% greater than 2011</a>. This has inevitably resulted in building of an entire global ecosystem that supports the phenomenon of equity crowdfunding. One of the things that is critical to equity crowdfunding and quite heavily linked to equity crowdfunding portals is the process of shareholder communication which is facilitated by the portals.\r\n\r\nToday, the democratization of financial investments has not only led to <a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-money/business-funding/equity-crowd-funding-is-the-next-evolution-of-capital-raising/article23596011/">massive economic boom</a> in terms of <a href="http://ncfacanada.org">creation of jobs</a>, but also there is <a href="http://ncfacanada.org">massive capital influx</a> into businesses because of the optimization of investments carried out by portals.  Investors that are contributing all of this capital today neither need to be extremely high net worth individuals, nor do they need to be secluded from the bulk of business deals taking place elsewhere in their country or around the world. Because the portals provide a communication and networking platform, the cost of managing all the investors for the entrepreneur has significantly gone down. Apart from costs, what is even more important is the fact that the investors who contributed their capital in the company now referred as shareholders can monitor and discuss the progress of the company. They can either pool in their ideas on how to steer the company for the future, how to handle challenges and how to make them even better in terms of product or returns on financial investment or, they can just sit passively and observe the work of the entrepreneur. In all the cases described above, <a href="http://prodigynetworkblog.com/uncategorized/crowdfunding-fosters-transparency-and-engagement/">the transparency and the openness regarding company’s progress</a>, and the ability to interact with other fellow shareholders or the entrepreneur at any time via a safe and secured communication platform makes the entire process fluid and functional. Shareholders need not to fly from different areas and schedule meetings which might not work for everyone. Instead the shareholders can all communicate online and discuss issues relevant to the venture just like they would if they had a shareholder meeting with all the concerned parties.\r\n\r\nTo further explore the importance of shareholder communication, let us look at the alternative. Imagine you invested USD 10,000 in a startup a year ago. When you signed the cheque, you knew that the company was in dire need of funds to survive and the entrepreneur had explained the ways he was going to use the investment. But unfortunately since then, a year or two has passed and you have not heard even once from the company you invested in. You barely remember even the company’s name, you don’t know who else invested in the company and you are stuck with all the negativity and wondering why in the first place you made that investment call.  Now this, is a bad situation that nobody wants to be in. If only there was a way to be in contact with the entrepreneur from a remote location, be in touch with all the other investors who contributed the capital along with you, and be informed about the progress of the company without spending any capitals on arranging such meetups, your life would be so much easier and efficient. That is where shareholder communication comes in, and the importance of the equity crowdfunding portal’s job becomes evident.  In order to take high profile decisions regarding the company such as deciding CEO succession, or executive compensation, or deciding on <a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2013/12/17/good-corporate-governance-is-only-good-if-it-serves-shareholders-well/">corporate governance practices</a> or even just staying in the loop requires that there is no gap in communication. Like discussed above, if the gap develops, it leads to a horrible situation for both the entrepreneur and the shareholder because the shareholder is no longer supportive of what the entrepreneur does. He or she is disengaged, and since there is no communication, there is no space for building any trust or long lasting relationship which is customary and necessary for a company to survive since the company is not owned by one person, it belongs to a pool of people and if the pool does not contribute, the chances of developing a fragile governing structure becomes very easy.', 'Common Questions: Why is shareholder communication critical?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 22:25:51', '2015-05-12 22:25:51', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=752', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(753, 10, '2015-05-12 22:26:23', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'At KoreConX, one of our central goals is helping both entrepreneurs and investors explore the global phenomenon that equity crowdfunding has become; in order to do this, we try to equip you with the vocabulary and business know-how you need to navigate the equity crowdfunding space.\r\n\r\nA central skill for any investor to possess in this arena is the ability to read financial statements, and to successfully extract useful information from them via meaningful interpretation and analysis. A diverse range of financial reports exist, from balance sheets to income and cash flow statements; as such, it can sometimes be difficult to read novel financial documents without becoming intimated.\r\n\r\nIn this article, we will try to equip you with the tips you need to get through a financial report, and maybe even get something out of it!\r\n\r\nThe Key Tips:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>To begin with, it’s important to understand which financial statements to use. Typically, the three documents central to analysis for investment purposes are the balance sheet, the income statement, and the cash flow statement. While other documents exist (<em>g.</em>, the statement of shareholders’ equity, and the statement of retained earnings), these rarely contain highly important information, so financial analysts tend to pass them by. Note also that, while many people tend to de-emphasize the cash flow statement, it contains <em>vital</em> information – pay attention to it!</li>\r\n	<li>Once you know which documents you’ll be working with, try to get to know some financial jargon. Countless articles exist that should help you clarify any necessary terms, so if you’re at a loss, try Googling a cluster of keywords like “What is a margin high margin low margin finance”, and an article explaining related content should come up. Financial dictionaries also exist, but realistically, the Internet has more than enough terminology-related information.</li>\r\n	<li>It’s also wise to remain aware that financial statements don’t reveal everything that you need to know in order to make a wise investment decision. The state of the economy, the industry, the competition, assorted market forces, technological change, the quality of the company’s management, the quality of the company’s workforce… all these and more are variables that financial statements won’t reveal, but that are worth delving into if you’re trying to make a very well-weighted investment decision.</li>\r\n	<li>Read the auditor’s report prior to delving into financial statements! Investors should, generally, only consider investing in companies with audited financial statements, as these are a requirement for all publicly traded companies. If the auditor’s report is less-than-stellar, stay away!</li>\r\n	<li>Be aware of “<a href="http://www.investopedia.com/articles/basics/06/financialreporting.asp">GAAP</a>”! GAAP (generally accepted accounting principles) are used to prepare financial statements, and you should understand at least two GAAP conventions in order to be confident in your analyses: historical cost, and accrual accounting. Historical cost means that assets are valued at their purchase price (their historical cost), which maybe different than their current market value). <a href="http://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/accrualaccounting.asp">Accrual accounting</a> means that economic events are recognized by matching revenues to expenses when the transaction occurs rather than when the payment is made, which allows current cash inflows and outflows to be combined with expected cash inflows and outflows for a more accurate picture of how a company’s doing at the moment.</li>\r\n	<li>It’s important to be aware of terms like “10-K”, “10-Q”, “8-K”, and “Forms 3 to 5” – you’ll encounter all these documents in conducting analysis! The 10-K is the annual report, providing a summary of the corporation’s activities for the entirety of the last year. The 10-Q is a quarterly report that provides the investor with useful information about the last three months of the company’s history. The 8-K describes any major events that could impact the company, and Forms 3 to 5 reflect changes in ownership of stock by directors, officers, and major stockholders.</li>\r\n	<li>You should also be aware of a few key terms. The price/earnings ratio compares the price of a stock to its earnings (<em>e.</em>, market value per share of stock divided by earnings per share of stock). The dividend payout ratio shows you the amount of a company’s earnings that are paid out to investors (<em>i.e.</em>, yearly dividend per share divided by earnings per share). The return on sales tells you how efficiently a company is running its operations, as it measures profit produced per dollar of sales (<em>i.e.</em>, net income before taxes divided by sales). The return on assets shows you how well a company uses its assets (<em>i.e.</em>, net income divided by total assets), and return on equity measures how well a company earns money for investors (<em>i.e.</em>, net income divided by shareholders’ equity). Finally, margins are important: the gross margin tells you how much revenue is left after the direct costs of producing and selling the product have been factored in (<em>i.e.</em>, gross profit divided by net sales/revenues), and the operating margin tells you how well a company controls costs by factoring in any expenses <em>not</em> related directly to production and sales (<em>i.e.</em>, operating profit divided by net sales/revenues).</li>\r\n	<li>Understand liquidity ratios and cash flow formulas! A relatively good note on them can be found <a href="http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/reading-financial-reports-for-dummies-cheat-sheet.html">here</a>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nCumulatively, then, reading a financial report isn’t as bad as it seems! Just follow the above tips, and you should be on your way to informed financial analysis (and, subsequently, well-weighted investment decisions).', 'Common Questions: How do you read a financial report?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 22:26:23', '2015-05-12 22:26:23', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=753', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(754, 10, '2015-05-12 22:26:51', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX feel that unless all of us have a thorough understanding about the system of equity crowdfunding, it would be very hard to follow the system even if all the <strong>legislative blocks</strong> were removed. The equity crowdfunding portals around the globe are doing a fantastic job of <strong>standardizing and automating</strong> the entire process of investment via equity crowdfunding. What this entails, and we have mentioned this in the previous articles as well, is the presence of same steps that anyone would encounter in an investment deal outside of equity crowdfunding. The only thing that changes due to the regulated and integrated nature of equity crowdfunding process is the way each old step is now conducted in an efficient manner. To give one an idea about which steps we are referring to, imagine you are an investor and you want to view the listings on a particular equity crowdfunding portal. In order to be listed, the portal must be able to qualify you as an eligible investor for their portal. To do that, they would carry out due diligence, background checks and monitor your business plan. Once approved, and say you invested in some company X, you would then communicate with other shareholders and the entrepreneur to monitor the progress of the company and its profits via the equity crowdfunding portal. These are the very same steps one would have to go through even if one was far removed from an equity crowdfunding world. The due diligence, background checks and all the thorough examination of records would have to take place manually or independently. So in essence then, the steps of a business deal are not being altered, the steps are just performed in a more efficient and integrated manner. With all the standardization and integrated processing, managing one’s shareholders, like discussed above also is not a new concept, it is only being conducted in a more efficient manner. So how should one manage one’s shareholders once they have signed an equity crowdfunding deal?\r\n\r\nManaging one’s shareholders via equity crowdfunding is slightly different than just managing them as part of other kinds of investment. What distinguishes the two forms of managing shareholders is the presence of an equity crowdfunding portal which provides the platform to connect, network and share highly confidential information from remote areas on a secured server offered by the portal. Compared to the past when shareholder meetings took place in person, and required everyone to travel to a single location, now the shareholders can schedule regular meetings from their home and still be connected and on top of everything that concerns them.\r\n\r\nHowever, there are things that the entrepreneur should be more concerned about. With the rise of all the portals, and their attempt at making the process more efficient, if the entrepreneur is not up to task, or is not regular in his communications, that can send a very negative vibe to the shareholders.\r\n\r\nTo manage the shareholders in an optimal manner requires firstly that the entrepreneur knows his investors. Knowing the investors or shareholders goes far beyond just sending them updates or asking for more money. It involves building a professional relationship where the worries and struggles of the company are shared by all and not by one.\r\n\r\nThe entrepreneur also needs to regularly e-mail about the progress of the company so that trust, transparency and openness within the boundaries of the company are norms that are expected of everyone. Having a proactive attitude and taking the initiative to sharing new updates regarding internal accounting and auditing, financial information, product and manufacturing, research and development, marketing strategies and sales forecasts should happen regularly.\r\n\r\nThe entrepreneur should also reach out to collect shareholder feedback via polls and personal communication in a way that makes shareholders feel as though their views are really being taken into consideration. Obtaining feedback and keeping abreast of shareholders in a personal way can significantly affect their willingness to support you when the going gets tough, and makes for a better experience for everyone!', 'Common Questions: How should I manage my shareholders?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-12 22:26:51', '2015-05-12 22:26:51', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=754', 0, 'post', '', 0),
